observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Disbursing Officer maintain his cashbooks accordingly by adopting the following measures:

Update the cashbooks daily based on the Disbursement Vouchers already paid and given to the Accounting Office;
Closely monitor cash balance by reconciling daily the cash on hand balance in the cashbooks and physical existence of cash on hand to ensure the accuracy;
Strictly observe the rule that there should be no accommodation of cash advances by officers and employees; and
Reconcile the cashbook balances with the accounting records every end of the month. Make the necessary corrections should there be some differences between these records.

We recommended that the Management:

Submit to the audit team the approved time extensions of the subjected projects, if available, to avoid the issuance of Notice of Charge;
For CY 2021 transactions, attach the approved extensions of contract time, if there is, with the Disbursement Vouchers to support payment;
For procurement of Goods, completely fill-out the important dates or periods in the POs, Bidding Documents, Delivery Receipts and IARs; and
Closely monitor the implementation of projects through a GANTT Chart and advice the contractors to monitor also their compliance with their contracts to avoid the delayed implementation of projects and adverse findings like liquidated damages.

13.14	We recommended that Management:
Require the accountable officers, especially those with long overdue cash advances, to settle their account or refund their un-liquidated cash advance or else criminal or administrative case may be filed against them pursuant to CSC Memorandum Circular No. 23, series of 2019;
Comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances;
Initiate the request for the write-off of 10-year account balances of accountable officers who have already died and those who have absconded but with unliquidated cash advances, in accordance with the provisions under COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;
Properly classify the Accountable Officers whether still employed, resigned or deceased in order for the Municipality to properly plan the courses of action to be made in the settlement of the cash advances; and
Refrain from granting additional cash advances to officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances.
13.15	The management accepted the audit findings and had shown its commitment in complying with the audit recommendations.

We recommended management to:

Submit the RDS of the missing inventory costing P6,091,582.00;
Refund the missing inventory cost if submission of RDS cannot be made;
Require the Accounting Office to post-audit the individual RDS whenever there is distribution of welfare goods and to submit the RDS/RIS as part of documentary requirements whenever there is distribution; and
Refrain from using government funds to favor only the welfare of the officials and employees of the LGU and not the general public.

We recommended that Management:

Require the accountable officers, especially those with long overdue cash advances, to settle their account or refund their un-liquidated cash advance at once or else criminal or administrative case may be filed against them pursuant to CSC Memorandum Circular No. 23, series of 2019;
Comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 in the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances;
Ensure the settlement of outstanding cash advances of outgoing elected officials and employees before issuing their certificates of clearance;
Initiate the request for the write-off and/or adjustment of 10-year account balances for accountable officers who have already died and those who have absconded but with unliquidated cash advances in accordance with the provisions under COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;
Properly classify the Accountable Officers whether still employed, resigned or deceased in order for the Municipality to properly plan the courses of action to be made in the settlement of the cash advances;
Require the Municipal Accountant not to process cash advances of elected officials with purposes other than for official travel and those without approved travel order and itinerary of travel; and
Refrain from granting additional cash advances to officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances. The Accountant shall issue a Certification that the person has no outstanding cash advance based on accounting records in order for him to be granted additional cash advance. This document shall be an important requirement in all cash advance vouchers.

We recommended that Management:

Refrain from withholding additional retention money from payments to contractors after the project’s 50% completion in order to minimize the events where contractors request to withdraw their retention money before one (1) year from project completion to final acceptance;
Issue Certificate of Final Acceptance to contractors only after one (1) year from project completion;
Require the contractors to post Warranty Securities for the completed projects in CY 2020 and submit the certified true copies for audit references; and
For CY 2021, always require the contractors to post Warranty Securities after the issuance of Certificate of Final Acceptance or of the lapse of the defect liability period.

8. We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Head of the LDRRMO and other concerned officials to submit to the Audit Team the following requirements, to prevent suspension of the disbursements in audit:
8. Letter of Invitation or Offer and Contract or equivalent agreement with the training provider;
9. Documents to prove that the training package of P36,000.00 per participant or a total of P432,000.00 offered by the training provider was the most cost-efficient or most economical in the market or that the training provider was the only provider of underwater, rescue and retrieval training in the country;
10. A training design which includes a background or statement on the topography and/or conditions in the Municipality that would justify participation in the subject training design;
11. Documents showing that participants met the qualifications criteria set in the training design;
12. Documents citing valid justification or reasons why direct contracting was resorted to in the procurement of supplies and equipment amounting to P157,357.00;
13. Purchase Request and Purchase Order for the procurement of supplies and equipment.
